Pre-expoure prophylaxis (PreEP) is an HIV medicine given before sex to reduce the risk of HIV disease.
Tests have shown that PreEP significantly reduces the risk of transmission of HIV between patients at risk.
Application of PreEP before sex means that there are enough specific medicines in the patient’s body to prevent infection.
These drugs can be taken every day or at least two hours before sex.
Tested patients include homosexual or bisexual men, transsexual people and people with HIV positive partners who are not successfully treated.
Clinics shall designate eligible participants who sign consent to participation in the testing, including men, women, transsexual people and individuals with a partner whose HIV status is not yet controlled by the appropriate treatment.
People living and registered with GP in the UK can also apply to their local sexual health clinic and apply for potential participation in testing.
The program will be issued by taxpayers at £10 million and the NHS England has signed a contract this week to distribute medicines after obtaining an international public contract.
The trial period is proposed for the collection of clinical evidence and the assessment of the full potential of the PREP, its purpose, use and implementation on a large scale.
Simon Stevens added: ‘This important intervention should complement and fully exploit the ever-growing and increasingly successful efforts to prevent HIV.
