Red meat, dairy products and chocolate can relieve the symptoms of inflammatory bowel disease (IBD)
For your digestive system, red meat and dairy products can be a nightmare.
However, a new study suggests the opposite: a diet rich in animal protein and dairy products could help relieve symptoms of inflammatory bowel disease.
The incurable disease, which affects up to 1.3 million U.S. residents and 300,000 patients in the UK, causes abdominal pain and bloody diarrhea, weight loss and extreme fatigue.
Patients are usually reminded not to eat meat and milk products to relieve symptoms. However, Washington University researchers have found that the essential triptophan amino acid contained in the protein helps to create immune cells that promote bowel resistance.
Dr. Marco Colonna, head of the study, explained that immune cells protect the intestines and ensure that harmful microbes are removed from the food.
The number of inflammatory cells is balanced by the number of cells that promote tolerance and protect the body without damaging the sensitive tissue.
Once the weight bowls are inclined to the side of the inflammation, an inflammatory bowel disease may occur.
Research has identified the presence of immune cells supporting body tolerance in the stomach of mice with specific bacteria.
This bacteria requires the presence of tryptophan - one of the building blocks of proteins to form cells.
Professor Colonna said: “We have found a connection between one species of bacteria - Lactobacillus reuteri - which is a common part of intestinal microbioma and the development of cells that promote body tolerance.
The more tryptophan they had in their diet, the more they had these immune cells."
At the same time, he suggested that if it turned out that the same applies also to humans, then a combination of L. reuteri and a diet rich in tryptophan would help develop a more tolerable and less inflammatory intestinal environment.
Postgraduate researcher Dr. Luisa Cervantes-Barraganwas discovered within the study of a certain type of immune cells supporting body tolerance that one group of test mice had these cells, while the other group of same mice kept separately cells lacked.
It came from the fact that one group of mice has a different intestinal microbiome - a community of bacteria, viruses and moulds, which commonly reside in the gastrointestinal tract.
The musculature was tested by DNA sorting method and researchers found six types of bacteria in mice with immune cells missing a second group of mice.
The mice that were bred in a sterile environment and lacked a intestinal microbiom - so they did not develop this type of immune cells - were given the L. reuteri bacteria - and they formed immune cells.
In order to understand how bacteria affect the immune system, researchers developed L. reuteri in fluid and then transferred a small amount of fluid - without the bacteria - to undeveloped immune cells that were stored in isolation.
The immune cells evolved into tolerant cells.
After removal of the active ingredient from the liquid, it turned out to be a by-product of triptofane metabolism known as indolyl-3-acetic acid.
When researchers doubled the amount of tryptophan in the mouse diet, the number of these cells increased by 50 percent.
Dr. Cervantes-Barragan explained that people have the same tolerant cells as mice and most of us keep L. reuteri bacteria in their gastrointestinal tract.
It is not known whether the by-products of tryptophan from L. reuteri cause the development of cells in humans in the same way as mice, but defects in the genes associated with tryptophan have been found in humans with inflammatory bowel disease.
Dr. Cervantes-Barragan added: “Each of us should probably seek the development of these cells because they control the inflammation of the inner surface of the intestines.
Potentially high levels of tryptophan in the presence of L. reuteri can increase the cell population."
